Alexander Bolzhelarskiy
2019-08-08 11:40:11

Hi All! I recently passed Cucumber School. This was not the first touch of Cucumber for me. I have already setup a Cucumber project, read it‚Äôs documentation many times. But‚Ä¶ I did want to hear from Cucumber‚Äôs creators what concept they put inside of the framework, how they recommend to use it. The School itself was very interesting. However after the school some of my questions left unanswered. People from hello@cucumber.io suggested me asking the questions here. So here they are. I would appreciate the answers!

  1. Is a Feature (in Cucumber) and equivalent for User Story?
  2. Did I understand correctly that every Scenario is a test for a particular Acceptance Criteria?
  3. Creating ‚Äúsmall tests‚Äù that verify single acceptance criteria is very expensive. This is why usually UI tests are End-to-end happy path flows. How does the ‚Äúend-to-end happy path‚Äù concept matches to ‚Äútest an acceptance criteria‚Äù concept? Are they not too different and so UI tests will never follow the Cucumber Feature-based architecture? a. This article (https://www.testingexcellence.com/selenium-and-cucumber-ui-automation-challenges/) expresses my concerns too. Could you please tell me what is your vision to the issue of mismatching of Features and User Jorneys?
  4. As the main (basic) concept, who is supposed to write the Gerkin scenarios? Is it a QA or a Product Owner (or Business Analyst)? (Let‚Äôs agree that Developers will never do it)
  5. REST API tests are all about sending requests an parsing responses. Does it worth it to try and convert the API language (send GET request, send POST request with payload, parse response, check error message) to the Domain language? a. How do I call a step definition in a Domain-style if input data for my test contains only 15 values for payload of POST request and 15 values that I expect to get in a response of GET request? (What I in fact check is that the math works correctly)
  6. One of the reasons for deleting tests is: ‚Äúthe test has become unreliable, failing randomly. You‚Äôve tried to fix it but the effort will outweigh the benefit of it.‚Äù Does it not mean that the application has a defect here? Why don‚Äôt we focus on fixing the defect then? Deleting the test means just closing our eyes on the defect. What do I understand wrong here?
  7. Which option is better: to have a scenario for every found bug OR to create appropriate test case (scenario) and incorporate it to a particular feature?
  8. UI tests are usually executed after ‚ÄúQA Deployed‚Äù status. Developers will never run all their tests on their local env before pushing the changes to a git repository. Sometimes it‚Äôs even impossible. So having the tests ran on QA env. we get late response. And defects, found by the tests, can stay days/weeks/months in the backlog. What should we do with the failed tests? Ignore? Add a workaround? Or keep running them and see RED execution status?
  9. ‚ÄúFor every acceptance test there should be a corresponding unit test‚Äù - Unit tests must cover both positive and negative scenarios. All of them. Should acceptance tests do the same? All the boundary values? All the classes of equivalence? Is it not too much for acceptance tests?

Why Selenium and Cucumber Should Not Be Used Together
Why we should not use Selenium and Cucumber to write UI Automated Tests? What are the challenges we face when we automate tests with Selenium and Cucumber?

From my little knowledge of cucumber so far, I get a clearer understanding employing cucumber when testing web UI or api testing/Rest- assured. Using it for unit testing i.e testing business application logic without a good programming knowledge might be hard. First when you write your feature file and bind it to the steps correctly and created your runner file,your test should be green. Thereafter,and in the case of UI testing when your failed to locate your element correctly for whatever reason,the test in cucumber will start to fail again. This is equally same when testing api. For example,you send your request to server requesting for a resource after providing the url and the necessary parameters, if the resource is available you are expected to get a status code 200 and your cucumber test result should be green.However,if you want to assert your result and want to make your test a negative test,if you change you expected result to e.g 201 and the actual is 200 as returned by the server response,then your test will fail.

I don‚Äôt know if anyone‚Äôs interested in going ‚Äúbehind the scenes‚Äù but since @Andrew Goodnough was asking about the language versions, you might be interested to know that the scripts (as in scripts for a movie, not as in bash scripts!) we use to develop and record the BDD with Cucumber/SpecFlow course are all open source, on GitHub:

https://github.com/cucumber-school/bdd-with-cucumber

We use AsciiDoc to write the scripts, and we have some GitHub actions that render the scripts as HTML. We use these during development of the videos to help us get them tight before we record them.

https://cucumber-school.github.io/bdd-with-cucumber/

Our process is, roughly:

  1. @seb, @gaspar or I write a ‚Äúcode storyboard‚Äù for a new chapter as a series of git commits in a branch in that repo (e.g. https://github.com/cucumber-school/bdd-with-cucumber/commits/chapter-03-code-ruby)
  2. We draft a script
  3. @Federico Iachetti adds shots to the script and we review it
  4. Once the script is tight, @Federico Iachetti records the shots (snippets of video) and one of us reads out the script as an audio track.
  5. @Arthur edits the video by fitting the video shots to the narrated audio
  6. We review and fix any snags in the edited video
  7. We write the questions and publish the new chapter on thinkific. That‚Äôs the work that goes into each new chapter! üí™

You can watch the work going on over in <#CCK3ZFSF9|school-devs> / <#CT14WESK0|school-devs-bots> and give the team some appreciation. üéâ

*Thread Reply:* Hey folks,

Sorry the code is a bit hard to find.

We actually use an orphaned git branch for each lesson, with one commit per "shot", and then duplicate those commits into the main branch for the scripts.

So for chapter 2 javascript, the commits are in https://github.com/cucumber-school/scripts/tree/chapter-02-code-js

If you look at https://github.com/cucumber-school/scripts/commits/chapter-02-code-js you'll see the flow of the whole lesson, and you could check out the code at any point in the narrative (if you have the git skills to do that).

We then "unroll" the code from those branches into the main branch, so those commits end up as snapshot copies of the repo here: https://github.com/cucumber-school/scripts/tree/main/content/bdd-with-cucumber/02/code/js

I hope that helps a bit. I haven't been able to figure out a nice user-friendly way to present this to people yet. Any advice or feedback on that would be very welcome! I know many of our users are only just learning git, so I need to find a way to explain this more simply, and make the code available in a way that's actually useful.
